tic world, and much more. He concludes with a rousing call for a return to Africa in studies of the Black Atlantic, resurrecting a critical notion of culture that allows us to transcend Western inventions of African while taking them into account.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aCultszAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aOrisha religionzAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aYoruba (African people)zAtlantic Ocean RegionxReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aBlack Atlantic.  aBrazilian Candomblé.  aCuban Santería.  aHaitian Vodou.  aYoruba-Atlantic.  acreolization.  aorisha worship.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022650638840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226506555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226506555/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles